  "For the reaction N2O4(g) <-> 2NO2(g), Kc = 4.6 x 10^-3 at 25 degrees C. A student initially places 0.50 M N2O4 in a flask. What are the approximate equilibrium concentrations?": "",
  "[N2O4] = 0.49 M, [NO2] = 0.048 M": "",
  "[N2O4] = 0.50 M, [NO2] = 0 M": "",
  "[N2O4] = 0 M, [NO2] = 1.00 M": "",
  "[N2O4] = 0.25 M, [NO2] = 0.25 M": "",
  "Using ICE: Kc = (2x)^2/(0.50-x) = 4.6x10^-3. Since K is small, x is small: 4x^2/0.50 = 4.6x10^-3, x = 0.024. [N2O4] = 0.476 ~ 0.49, [NO2] = 0.048.": "",
  "A chemist determines that at 700 K, the reaction H2(g) + I2(g) <-> 2HI(g) has Kc = 54.3. If [H2] = [I2] = 0.10 M and [HI] = 0.50 M, is the system at equilibrium? If not, which direction will it shift?": "",
  "Q = 54.3, system is at equilibrium": "",
  "Q = 25, Q < K, shifts left toward reactants": "",
  "Q = 25, Q < K, shifts right toward products": "",
  "Q = 25, system is at equilibrium": "",
  "Q = [HI]^2/([H2][I2]) = (0.50)^2/(0.10 x 0.10) = 25. Since Q (25) < K (54.3), the reaction shifts right to make more HI.": "",
